import tweepy
import pandas as pd
import time

#  Twitter API v2 Credentials (Replace with your own)
BEARER_TOKEN = "AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAOJ%2FzwEAAAAAYiXKZxFg0MZOFM6qUIPXkWYaxOM%3Dg1RdWlxuCQPNM0dSqhn9ut7PtQB1Cuax1MqHQ4zU1dVP0HwNaP"

# Authenticate with Twitter API v2
client = tweepy.Client(bearer_token=BEARER_TOKEN)

# Function to fetch tweets using Twitter API v2
def fetch_tweets(query="Bose New QuietComfort Ultra ", max_results=50):
    tweets_data = []
    
    try:
        # Fetch tweets using Twitter API v2
        response = client.search_recent_tweets(
            query=query,
            tweet_fields=["created_at", "public_metrics"],  # Fetch likes, retweets, etc.
            max_results=max_results
        )

        # Process fetched tweets
        if response.data:
            for tweet in response.data:
                tweets_data.append({
                    "Tweet": tweet.text,
                    "Date": tweet.created_at,
                    "Likes": tweet.public_metrics["like_count"],
                    "Retweets": tweet.public_metrics["retweet_count"]
                })
        else:
            print(" No tweets found for the query!")

    except tweepy.TweepyException as e:
        print(f" API Error: {e}. Waiting for 15 minutes... ")
        time.sleep(900)  # Wait 15 minutes if rate limit is hit
        return fetch_tweets(query, max_results)

    return pd.DataFrame(tweets_data)

# Main function to fetch tweets and save to CSV
def main():
    print(" Fetching tweets...")
    tweets_df = fetch_tweets()
    
    # Save to CSV
    if not tweets_df.empty:
        tweets_df.to_csv("Bose New QuietComfort Ultra.csv", index=False)
        print(" Tweets successfully saved to tweets_noise_bose.csv")
    else:
        print(" No data found, nothing to save.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

from selenium import webdriver
from selenium.webdriver.chrome.service import Service
from selenium.webdriver.common.by import By
from selenium.webdriver.common.keys import Keys
from webdriver_manager.chrome import ChromeDriverManager
import pandas as pd
import time

#  ASIN of the product (Replace with actual ASIN)
asin = "B0DK96DPY6"

# Initialize Selenium WebDriver
options = webdriver.ChromeOptions()
options.add_argument("--headless")  # Run in headless mode (no UI)
options.add_argument("--disable-gpu")
options.add_argument("--no-sandbox")
options.add_argument("--window-size=1920,1080")
options.add_argument("start-maximized")
options.add_argument("disable-infobars")
options.add_argument("--disable-extensions")

# Install WebDriver and open browser
driver = webdriver.Chrome(service=Service(ChromeDriverManager().install()), options=options)

# Function to fetch reviews using Selenium
def fetch_reviews():
    reviews = []
    page_num = 1
    base_url = f"https://www.amazon.in/product-reviews/{asin}/ref=cm_cr_arp_d_paging_btm_next_"

    while len(reviews) < 30:  # Ensuring at least 30 reviews
        print(f" Fetching reviews from page {page_num}...")

        page_url = f"{base_url}{page_num}?pageNumber={page_num}"
        driver.get(page_url)
        time.sleep(5)  # Allow page to load

        # Scroll to load all reviews
        driver.find_element(By.TAG_NAME, "body").send_keys(Keys.END)
        time.sleep(3)

        # Find all review elements
        review_elements = driver.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".review")

        if not review_elements:
            print(" No more reviews found. Stopping pagination.")
            break

        for review in review_elements:
            try:
                author = review.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".a-profile-name").text.strip()
                rating = review.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".review-rating").text.strip().split()[0]
                date = review.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".review-date").text.strip()

                title_element = review.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".review-title")
                title = title_element.text.strip() if title_element else "No Title"

                content_element = review.find_element(By.CSS_SELECTOR, ".review-text")
                content = content_element.text.strip() if content_element else "No Content"

                verified_element = review.find_elements(By.CSS_SELECTOR, "span.a-size-mini")
                verified = verified_element[0].text.strip() if verified_element else "Not Verified"

                reviews.append({
                    "author": author,
                    "rating": rating,
                    "title": title,
                    "content": content.replace("Read more", ""),
                    "date": date,
                    "verified": verified
                })

                if len(reviews) >= 30:
                    break
            except Exception as e:
                print(f" Skipping a review due to missing data: {e}")

        page_num += 1
        time.sleep(3)  # Delay to avoid detection

    return reviews

# Main function to fetch reviews and save to CSV
def main():
    print(f" Fetching reviews for ASIN: {asin}...")

    reviews = fetch_reviews()
    
    if reviews:
        # Save extracted data into CSV
        df = pd.DataFrame(reviews)
        filename = f"reviews_{asin}.csv"
        df.to_csv(filename, index=False, encoding='utf-8')
        print(f" Successfully saved {len(reviews)} reviews to {filename}")
    else:
        print(" No reviews found.")

    # Close the browser
    driver.quit()

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

import pandas as pd
import re

# Load dataset
file_path = "Noise Master Buds Combined Review.csv"  
df = pd.read_csv(file_path, dtype=str, encoding="ISO-8859-1")

# Select relevant columns
df = df[['title', 'content']].dropna()

# Function to clean and tokenize text data
def preprocess_text(text):
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = text.lower()  # Convert to lowercase
        text = re.sub(r'\W', ' ', text)  # Remove special characters
        text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)  # Remove numbers
        text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()  # Remove extra spaces
        return text
    return ""

# Apply text preprocessing
df["Processed_Title"] = df["title"].apply(preprocess_text)
df["Processed_Content"] = df["content"].apply(preprocess_text)

# Create corpus
corpus = df["Processed_Title"].tolist() + df["Processed_Content"].tolist()
corpus

# Download VADER lexicon (only needed once)
nltk.download('vader_lexicon')

# Load dataset (assuming 'df' is already loaded in memory)
# Select relevant columns and drop missing values
df = df[['title', 'content', 'rating']].dropna()

# Function to clean text
def clean_text(text):
    if isinstance(text, str):
        text = text.lower()  # Convert to lowercase
        text = re.sub(r'\W', ' ', text)  # Remove special characters
        text = re.sub(r'\d+', '', text)  # Remove numbers
        text = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', text).strip()  # Remove extra spaces
        return text
    return ""

# Apply text cleaning
df["Cleaned_Title"] = df["title"].apply(clean_text)
df["Cleaned_Content"] = df["content"].apply(clean_text)

# Initialize VADER Sentiment Intensity Analyzer
sia = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Function to apply VADER Sentiment Analysis
def get_vader_sentiment(text):
    score = sia.polarity_scores(text)['compound']
    if score >= 0.05:
        return "Positive"
    elif score <= -0.05:
        return "Negative"
    else:
        return "Neutral"

# Function to apply TextBlob Sentiment Analysis
def get_textblob_sentiment(text):
    polarity = TextBlob(text).sentiment.polarity
    if polarity > 0:
        return "Positive"
    elif polarity < 0:
        return "Negative"
    else:
        return "Neutral"

# Apply sentiment analysis on cleaned text
df["VADER_Sentiment_Title"] = df["Cleaned_Title"].apply(get_vader_sentiment)
df["VADER_Sentiment_Content"] = df["Cleaned_Content"].apply(get_vader_sentiment)
df["TextBlob_Sentiment_Title"] = df["Cleaned_Title"].apply(get_textblob_sentiment)
df["TextBlob_Sentiment_Content"] = df["Cleaned_Content"].apply(get_textblob_sentiment)

# Display the first few rows with sentiment analysis results
print(df[["title", "VADER_Sentiment_Title", "TextBlob_Sentiment_Title"]].head())
print(df[["content", "VADER_Sentiment_Content", "TextBlob_Sentiment_Content"]].head())

print(df["VADER_Sentiment_Content"].value_counts())
print(df["TextBlob_Sentiment_Content"].value_counts())

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Count the number of positive sentiment reviews using VADER
positive_vader_counts = df["VADER_Sentiment_Content"].value_counts().get("Positive", 0)

# Calculate the percentage of positive reviews
total_reviews = len(df["VADER_Sentiment_Content"])
positive_percentage = (positive_vader_counts / total_reviews) * 100

# Create an advanced descriptive visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
sns.barplot(x=["Positive Sentiment"], y=[positive_vader_counts], palette="Greens_r", edgecolor="black")

# Annotate the bar with count and percentage
plt.text(0, positive_vader_counts/2, f"{positive_vader_counts} Reviews\n({positive_percentage:.2f}%)",
         ha='center', fontsize=14, fontweight='bold', color="black")

# Enhancing the visualization
plt.title(" Positive Sentiment Reviews (VADER)", fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.ylabel("Number of Reviews", fontsize=14)
plt.xticks(fontsize=14)
plt.yticks(fontsize=14)
plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.6)
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import nltk
from nltk.sentiment.vader import SentimentIntensityAnalyzer
nltk.download('vader_lexicon')

# Initialize VADER analyzer
sid = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

# Compute sentiment scores
sentiments_df = pd.DataFrame([sid.polarity_scores(review) for review in corpus2])

# Get top 5 negative reviews
top_negative_reviews = sentiments_df.sort_values('neg', ascending=False).head(5)

# Plot horizontal bar graph for negative scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.barh(top_negative_reviews.index.astype(str), top_negative_reviews['neg'])
plt.xlabel('Negative Sentiment Score')
plt.title('Top 5 Most Negative Reviews (by VADER)')
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.show()
